'''Elizabeth B. French''' (born 1931) is a former warden of [[Ashburne Hall]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manchester.ac.uk/undergraduate/accommodation/display/index.htm?offset%3D0%26sort%3Dname%26sortdir%3Dascending%26res%3D66928%26catering%3DNoPref%26distance%3D10%26singlesex%3DNoPref%26singlesexareas%3DNoPref%26ugpg%3DNoPref%26adapted%3DNoPref%26computer%3DNoPref%26submit%3D%26searchtype%3Dsimple |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-04-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090831215630/http://www.manchester.ac.uk/undergraduate/accommodation/display/index.htm?offset=0&sort=name&sortdir=ascending&res=66928&catering=NoPref&distance=10&singlesex=NoPref&singlesexareas=NoPref&ugpg=NoPref&adapted=NoPref&computer=NoPref&submit=&searchtype=simple |archivedate=2009-08-31 |df= }}</ref> Manchester, former director of the [[British School at Athens]] and an authority in [[Mycenae]]an archaeology, especially pottery and terracotta figurines.
==Early life== Elizabeth B. French was born in 1931.{{citation required|date=December 2015}}
==Career== French developed a detailed classification scheme for a series of Mycenaean [[terra cotta]] figurines dating from the [[Late Helladic]] period (c.1500 - 1100 B.C.).<ref>E. B. French 1971 ‘The Development of Mycenaean Terracotta Figurines’, Annual of the British School of Archaeology at Athens 66, 101–87.</ref> She coined the term ''[[Wiktionary:kourotrophos|kourotrophos]]'' for a particular class of these artifacts depicting a woman holding a child.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Trckova-Flamee | first = Alena |date=September 2005 | title = The Mycenaean Terracotta Figurine from the Royal Museums of Art and History in Brussels | journal = ANISTORITON: ArtHistory | volume = 9 | pages = O053 | url = http://www.anistor.co.hol.gr/english/enback/o053.htm | accessdate = 2006-04-16 | format = &ndash; <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=author%3ATrckova-Flamee+intitle%3AThe+Mycenaean+Terracotta+Figurine+from+the+Royal+Museums+of+Art+and+History+in+Brussels&as_publication=ANISTORITON%3A+ArtHistory&as_ylo=2005&as_yhi=2005&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup> |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060211082352/http://www.anistor.co.hol.gr/english/enback/o053.htm |archivedate = February 11, 2006}} </ref> She has been involved in excavation and publication of archaeological excavation at [[Mycenae]] for many years and recently completed a survey of the remains around Mycenae in collaboration with the [[Archaeological Society of Athens]].<ref>S. Iakovides and E. B. French, Archaeological Atlas of Mycenae, 2003</ref> She wrote an account of the monuments and history of [[Mycenae]] itself.<ref>E.B. French, Mycenae, Agamemnon's Capital, 2002</ref> Her joint publication with P.S. Stockhammer, 'Correlating recent research: the pottery of Mycenae and Tiryns in the second half of the 13th Century BC', Annual of the British School at Athens, 106 (2009) 175-232 is the first attempt to align discoveries at the two most important Mycenaean sites.
