'''Maja Margita Gunn''' (born 1978)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ratsit.se/19780131-Maja_Margita_Gunn_Arsta/iTiV9FLe_n0v2jO8hXB-snmVEvoBAF8mGv1SG6fi_5g|title=Maja Gunn|publisher=ratsit|accessdate=16 January 2018 |language=Swedish}}</ref> is a Swedish [[fashion designer]], design researcher and academic who has specialized in lesbian and gender clothing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genderdesign.org/about-igdn/who-we-are/maja-gunn/|title=Maja Gunn|publisher=International Gender Design Network|accessdate=16 January 2018 |language=}}</ref><ref name=dt>{{cite web|url=http://www.dt.se/kultur/gunn-fran-ludvika-undersoker-vad-vi-berattar-med-plaggen|title=Gunn från Ludvika undersöker vad vi berättar med plaggen|author=Ekebjär, Cecilia|publisher=dt|date=17 October 2015|accessdate=16 January 2018 |language=Swedish}}</ref> In December 2017, she was appointed Professor of Crafts at the [[Gothenburg University]] Design School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldwebbhdk.gu.se/en/personal/maja-gunn|title=HDK: Crafts and design at Steneby|publisher=University of Gothenburg|accessdate=16 January 2018 |language=}}</ref>
==Early life and education== Born in [[Hallsberg]], central Sweden, on 31 January 1978, Maja Margita Gunn was brought up in [[Ludvika]]. After studying fashion at [[Stockholm University]] and at the [[Utrecht School of the Arts]] in the Netherlands, she graduated in fashion and costume design at [[Stockholm]]'s [[Konstfack]] in 2005.<ref name=dt/> In 2016, she earned a doctorate from the [[Swedish School of Textiles]] in [[Borås]] with a dissertation on ''Body acts queer: Clothing as a performative challenge to heteronormativity''.<ref name=gp>{{cite book|url=http://www.gp.se/kultur/mode-kropp-och-oskrivna-regler-1.4819022|title=Mode, kropp och oskrivna regler|author=Ekström-Frisk, Eleonor|publisher=''GP''|date=10 November 2017|language=Swedish}}</ref><ref name="Gunn2016">{{cite book|last=Gunn|first=Maja|title=Body Acts Queer: Clothing as a Performative Challenge to Heteronormativity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TW-eAQAACAAJ|year=2016|publisher=Högskolan i borås|isbn=978-91-88269-16-4}}</ref>
==Career== Gunn has worked as a costume designer for [[Sveriges Television|SVT Swedish Television]] and in fashion at [[H&M]]. She worked for a couple of years designing items for the ladies collections at [[Marc Jacobs]] in [[New York City|New York]]. While in the United States, she also designed costumes for television and theatre.<ref name=gp/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.svenskfilmdatabas.se/sv/item/?type=PERSON&itemid=396462|title=Maja Gunn|publisher=Svensk Filmdatabas|accessdate=16 January 2018 |language=Swedish}}</ref> More recently, she has created items for the lesbian and gay community, exhibiting her work at Liljevalchs in Stockholm (2015)<ref name=dt/> and at the Textile Museum in Borås (2017).<ref name=gp/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://textilmuseet.se/utstallningararkiv/majagunnplay.5.1e83601b15d0aeb60b0a6448.html|title=Maja Gunn: Play|publisher=Textil Museet|accessdate=16 January 2018 |language=Swedish}}</ref> In an interview with Cecilia Ekebjär of the Swedish ''dt'', she summed up her approach as follows: "I am interested in materiality, the relationship between body, clothes and gender."<ref name=dt/>
In December 2017, Maja Gunn was appointed professor of arts and crafts at [[Gothenburg University]]'s Steneby Design School, providing special focus on fashion design.<ref name=gp/>
